#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:5
msgid "FAQ"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:7
msgid ""
"This FAQ contains answers to many questions asked on IRC and the mailing "
"list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:11
msgid "How do I compile code?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:13
msgid ""
"See the :ref:`Emscripten Tutorial <Tutorial>` and :ref:`emcc <emccdoc>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:17
msgid "Why do I get errors building basic code and the tests?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:19
msgid ""
"All the tests in the :ref:`Emscripten test suite <emscripten-test-suite>` "
"are known to build and pass on our test infrastructure, so if you see "
"failures locally, it is likely that there is some problem with your "
"environment. (Rarely, there may be temporary breakage, but never on a tagged "
"release version.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:24
msgid ""
"First call ``emcc --check``, which runs basic sanity checks and prints out "
"useful environment information. If that doesn't help, follow the "
"instructions in :ref:`verifying-the-emscripten-environment`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:28
msgid ""
"You might also want to go through the :ref:`Tutorial` again, as it is "
"updated as Emscripten changes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:31
msgid ""
"Also make sure that you have the necessary requirements for running "
"Emscripten as specified in the :ref:`SDK <sdk-download-and-install>` "
"section, including new-enough versions of the dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:37
msgid "I tried something: why doesn’t it work?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:39
msgid "Some general steps that might help figure things out:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:41
msgid ""
"See if the problem happens without optimizations (`-O0`, or not specifying "
"any optimization level). Without optimizations, emscripten enables many "
"assertions at compile and runtime, which may catch a problem and display an "
"error message with a suggestion for how to fix it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:45
msgid "Search the documentation on this site."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:46
msgid ""
"Check if there is a test for the failing functionality in the :ref:"
"`Emscripten test suite <emscripten-test-suite>` (run ``grep -r`` in **test/"
"**). They should all pass (with only rare exceptions), so they provide "
"concrete \"known-good\" examples of how various options and code are used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:54
msgid "Do I need to change my build system to use Emscripten?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:56
msgid ""
"In most cases you will be able to use your project's current build system "
"with Emscripten. See :ref:`Building-Projects`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:61
msgid "Why is code compilation slow?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:63
msgid ""
"Emscripten makes some trade-offs that make the generated code faster and "
"smaller, at the cost of longer link times. For example, we build parts of "
"the standard library with `-flto` (Link Time Optimization), which enables "
"some additional optimizations, but can take longer to build.  We also (in "
"optimized builds) run the Binaryen optimizer on the entire output even "
"without LTO."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:69
msgid ""
"You can determine what compilation steps take longest by compiling with "
"``EMCC_DEBUG=1`` in the environment and then reviewing the debug logs (by "
"default in ``/tmp/emscripten_temp``). Note that compiling in debug mode "
"takes longer than normal, because we print out a lot of intermediate steps "
"to disk, so it's useful for debugging but not for actual compiling."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:75
msgid "The main tips for improving build time are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:77
msgid ""
"Use ``-O0`` for fast iteration builds. You can still compile with higher "
"optimization levels, but specifying ``-O0`` during link will make the link "
"step much faster."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:81
msgid "Compile on a machine with more cores:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:83
msgid ""
"For compiling your source files, use a parallel build system (for example, "
"in ``make`` you can do something like ``make -j8`` to run using 8 cores)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:85
msgid ""
"For the link step, Emscripten can run some optimizations in parallel "
"(specifically, Binaryen optimizations for Wasm, and our JavaScript "
"optimizations). Increasing the number of cores results in an almost linear "
"improvement. Emscripten will automatically use more cores if they are "
"available, but you can control that with ``EMCC_CORES=N`` in the environment "
"(which is useful if you have many cores but relatively less memory)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:94
msgid "Why does my code run slowly?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:96
msgid ""
"Make sure you optimize code by building with ``-O2`` (even more :ref:"
"`aggressive optimization <emcc-O3>` is available, at the cost of "
"significantly increased compilation time)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:106
msgid "Why is my compiled code big?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:108
msgid ""
"Make sure you build with ``-O3`` or ``-Os``, so the code is fully optimized "
"and minified. You should use the closure compiler, gzip compression on your "
"webserver, etc., see the :ref:`section on code size in Optimizing code "
"<optimizing-code-size>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:115
msgid "Why does compiling code that works on another machine give me errors?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:117
msgid ""
"Make sure you are using the Emscripten bundled system headers. Using :ref:"
"`emcc <emccdoc>` will do so by default, but problems may occur if you use "
"your local system headers with ``emcc``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:123
msgid "How can I reduce startup time?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:125
msgid ""
"Make sure that you are running an :ref:`optimized build <Optimizing-Code>` "
"(smaller builds are faster to start up)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:128
msgid ""
"Network latency is also a possible factor in startup time. Consider putting "
"the file loading code in a separate script element from the generated code "
"so that the browser can start the network download in parallel to starting "
"up the codebase (run the :ref:`file packager <packaging-files>` and put file "
"loading code in one script element, and the generated codebase in a later "
"script element)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:139
msgid ""
"How do I run a local webserver for testing / why does my program stall in "
"\"Downloading...\" or \"Preparing...\"?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:141
msgid ""
"That error can happen when loading the page using a ``file://`` URL, which "
"works in some browsers but not in others. Instead, it's best to use a local "
"webserver. For example, Python has one built in, ``python -m http.server`` "
"in Python 3 or ``python -m SimpleHTTPServer`` in Python 2. After doing that, "
"you can visit ``http://localhost:8000/``. You can also use ``emrun FILENAME."
"html`` (which will run a python webserver for you)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:148
msgid ""
"When doing quick local testing, another option than a local webserver is to "
"bundle everything into a single file, using ``-sSINGLE_FILE`` (as then no "
"XHRs will be made to ``file://`` URLs)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:152
msgid ""
"Otherwise, to debug this, look for an error reported on the page itself, or "
"in the browser devtools (web console and network tab), or in your "
"webserver's logging."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:158
msgid ""
"Why do I get ``machine type must be wasm32`` or ``unknown file type`` during "
"linking?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:160
msgid ""
"This means that one or more of this linker input files were not build by "
"Emscripten (or, more-specifically, not built for the correct target "
"architecture)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:163
msgid ""
"Most often the file in question will be an ELF file or Mach-O file built for "
"the host machine.  You can run the ``file`` command-line utility to see what "
"they actually contain."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:167
msgid "Common issues are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:169
msgid ""
"Attempting to link against libraries built for the host system.  For "
"example, if you have something like ``-L/usr/lib`` in your link command that "
"is almost always going to cause these errors since the libraries that exist "
"in those system directories are almost certainly not built with/for "
"Emscripten. This solution is to use Emscripten to build all the libraries "
"that you depend on, and never use host libraries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:175
msgid ""
"Some libraries or object files in your project were built using the host "
"compiler rather then the emscripten compiler.  If you are using autoconf or "
"cmake make sure you use the emconfigure/emmake wrapper, see :ref:`Building-"
"Projects`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:179
msgid ""
"LLVM IR from the old backend, if you built the project with a version before "
"1.39.0 (which used the old backend by default), and are doing an incremental "
"rebuild now. To fix that, do a complete rebuild from scratch of all your "
"project's files, including libraries (this error often happens if you have "
"prebuilt libraries from a third party; those must be recompiled too with the "
"new backend)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:188
msgid ""
"Why does my code fail to compile with an error message about inline assembly "
"(or ``{\"text\":\"asm\"}``)?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:190
msgid ""
"Emscripten cannot compile inline assembly code (unless that assembly code is "
"specifically written to target WebAssembly)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:193
msgid ""
"You will need to find where inline assembly is used, and disable it or "
"replace it with platform-independent code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:200
msgid "Why does my HTML app hang?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:202
msgid ""
"The browser event model uses *co-operative multitasking* — each event has a "
"\"turn\" to run, and must then return control to the browser event loop so "
"that other events can be processed. A common cause of HTML pages hanging is "
"JavaScript that does not complete and return control to the browser."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:207
msgid ""
"Graphical C++ apps typically have an infinite main loop in which event "
"handling, processing and rendering is done, followed by a delay to keep the "
"frame-rate right (``SDL_DELAY`` in :term:`SDL` apps). As the main loop does "
"not complete (is infinite), it cannot return control to the browser, and the "
"app will hang."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:212
msgid ""
"Apps that use an infinite main loop should be re-coded to put the actions "
"for a single iteration of the loop into a single \"finite\" function. In the "
"native build, this function can be run in an infinite loop as before. In the "
"Emscripten build it is set as the :ref:`main loop function <faq-how-run-"
"event-loop>` and will be called by the browser at a specified frequency."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:218
msgid ""
"There is more information on this topic in :ref:`emscripten-runtime-"
"environment`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:224
msgid "How do I run an event loop?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:226
msgid ""
"To run a C function repeatedly, use :c:func:`emscripten_set_main_loop` (this "
"is discussed in :ref:`emscripten-runtime-environment`). The related "
"functions in :ref:`emscripten.h <emscripten-h-browser-execution-"
"environment>` are also useful, allowing you to add events that block the "
"main loop, etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:231
msgid ""
"To respond to browser events use the SDL API in the normal way. There are "
"examples in the SDL tests (search for SDL in **test/runner.py**)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:234
msgid "See also: :ref:`faq-my-html-app-hangs`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:238
msgid "Why doesn't my SDL app work?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:240
msgid ""
"See the :term:`SDL` automatic tests for working examples: ``test/runner.py "
"browser``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:244
msgid "How do I link against system libraries like SDL, boost, etc.?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:246
msgid ""
"System libraries that are included with Emscripten are automatically linked "
"when you compile (just the necessary parts). This includes *libc*, *libc++* "
"(C++ standard library) and :term:`SDL`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:250
msgid ""
"Libraries not included with Emscripten (like Boost) must be compiled and "
"linked with the program just as if they were a module in the project."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:253
msgid ""
"There is a set of libraries ported to Emscripten for convenient use, "
"Emscripten Ports. See :ref:`Building-Projects`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:256
msgid ""
"Another option is to implement needed C APIs as JavaScript libraries (see "
"``--js-library`` in :ref:`emcc <emcc-js-library>` and :ref:`implement-c-in-"
"javascript`). Emscripten itself does this for *libc* (not including "
"*malloc*) and :term:`SDL` (but not *libc++* or *malloc*)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:263
msgid ""
"Unlike other compilers, you don't need ``-lSDL`` to include SDL (specifying "
"it will do no harm)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:265
msgid ""
"In the specific case of *Boost*, if you only need the boost headers then you "
"don't need to compile anything."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:270
msgid "What are my options for audio playback?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:272
msgid "Emscripten has partial support for SDL1 and 2 audio, and OpenAL."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:274
msgid ""
"To use SDL1 audio, include it as ``#include <SDL/SDL_mixer.h>``. You can use "
"it that way alongside SDL1, SDL2, or another library for platform "
"integration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:277
msgid ""
"To use SDL2 audio, include it as ``#include <SDL2/SDL_mixer.h>`` and use `-"
"sUSE_SDL_MIXER=2`.  Format support is currently limited to OGG, WAV, MID, "
"and MOD."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:283
msgid "How can my compiled program access files?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:285
msgid ""
"Emscripten uses a virtual file system that may be preloaded with data or "
"linked to URLs for lazy loading. See the :ref:`file-system-overview` for "
"more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:290
msgid "Why can't my code access a file in the same directory?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:292
msgid ""
"Emscripten-generated code running *in the browser* cannot access files in "
"the local file system. Instead you can use :ref:`preloading <emcc-preload-"
"file>` and :ref:`embedding <emcc-embed-file>` to work around the lack of "
"synchronous file IO. See :ref:`file-system-overview` for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:297
msgid ""
"It is possible to allow access to local file system for code running in "
"*node.js*, use the :ref:`NODEFS <filesystem-api-nodefs>` filesystem option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:304
msgid ""
"How can I tell when the page is fully loaded and it is safe to call compiled "
"functions?"
