#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:378
msgid "What does \"exiting the runtime\" mean? Why don't ``atexit()s`` run?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:380
msgid ""
"(You may need this answer if you see an error saying something like "
"``atexit() called, but EXIT_RUNTIME is not set`` or ``stdio streams had "
"content in them that was not flushed. you should set EXIT_RUNTIME to 1``.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:384
msgid ""
"By default Emscripten sets ``EXIT_RUNTIME=0``, which means that we don't "
"include code to shut down the runtime. That means that when ``main()`` "
"exits, we don't flush the stdio streams, or call the destructors of global C+"
"+ objects, or call ``atexit`` callbacks. This lets us emit smaller code by "
"default, and is normally what you want on the web: even though ``main()`` "
"exited, you may have something asynchronous happening later that you want to "
"execute."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:391
msgid ""
"In some cases, though, you may want a more \"commandline\" experience, where "
"we do shut down the runtime when ``main()`` exits. You can build with ``-"
"sEXIT_RUNTIME``, and then we will call ``atexits`` and so forth. When you "
"build with ``ASSERTIONS``, you should get a warning when you need this. For "
"example, if your program prints something without a newline,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:405
msgid ""
"If we don't shut down the runtime and flush the stdio streams, \"hello\" "
"won't be printed. In an ``ASSERTIONS`` build you'll get a notification "
"saying ``stdio streams had content in them that was not flushed. you should "
"set EXIT_RUNTIME to 1``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:414
msgid ""
"Why do functions in my C/C++ source code vanish when I compile to "
"WebAssembly?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:416
msgid ""
"Emscripten does dead code elimination of functions that are not called from "
"the compiled code. While this does minimize code size, it can remove "
"functions that you plan to call yourself (outside of the compiled code)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:420
msgid ""
"To make sure a C function remains available to be called from normal "
"JavaScript, it must be added to the `EXPORTED_FUNCTIONS <https://github.com/"
"emscripten-core/emscripten/blob/1.29.12/src/settings.js#L388>`_ using the "
"*emcc* command line. For example, to prevent functions ``my_func()`` and "
"``main()`` from being removed/renamed, run *emcc* with: ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:428
msgid ""
"`_main` should be in the export list, as in that example, if you have a "
"`main()` function. Otherwise, it will be removed as dead code; there is no "
"special logic to keep `main()` alive by default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:432
msgid ""
"`EXPORTED_FUNCTIONS` affects compilation to JavaScript. If you first compile "
"to an object file, then compile the object to JavaScript, you need that "
"option on the second command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:436
msgid ""
"If your function is used in other functions, LLVM may inline it and it will "
"not appear as a unique function in the JavaScript. Prevent inlining by "
"defining the function with :c:type:`EMSCRIPTEN_KEEPALIVE`: ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:442
msgid ""
"`EMSCRIPTEN_KEEPALIVE` also exports the function, as if it were on "
"`EXPORTED_FUNCTIONS`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:447
msgid ""
"All functions not kept alive through ``EXPORTED_FUNCTIONS`` or :c:type:"
"`EMSCRIPTEN_KEEPALIVE` will potentially be removed. Make sure you keep the "
"things you need alive using one or both of those methods."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:451
msgid "Exported functions need to be C functions (to avoid C++ name mangling)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:453
msgid ""
"Decorating your code with :c:type:`EMSCRIPTEN_KEEPALIVE` can be useful if "
"you don't want to have to keep track of functions to export explicitly, and "
"when these exports do not change. It is not necessarily suitable for "
"exporting functions from other libraries — for example it is not a good idea "
"to decorate and recompile the source code of the C standard library. If you "
"build the same source in multiple ways and change what is exported, then "
"managing exports on the command line is easier."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:461
msgid ""
"Running *emcc* with ``-sLINKABLE`` will also disable link-time optimizations "
"and dead code elimination. This is not recommended as it makes the code "
"larger and less optimized."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:465
msgid ""
"Another possible cause of missing code is improper linking of ``.a`` files. "
"The ``.a`` files link only the internal object files needed by previous "
"files on the command line, so the order of files matters, and this can be "
"surprising. If you are linking ``.a`` files, make sure they are at the end "
"of the list of files, and in the right order amongst themselves. "
"Alternatively, just use ``.so`` files instead in your project."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:472
msgid ""
"It can be useful to compile with ``EMCC_DEBUG=1`` set for the environment "
"(``EMCC_DEBUG=1 emcc ...`` on Linux, ``set EMCC_DEBUG=1`` on Windows). This "
"splits up the compilation steps and saves them in ``/tmp/emscripten_temp``. "
"You can then see at what stage the code vanishes (you will need to do ``llvm-"
"dis`` on the bitcode  stages to read them, or ``llvm-nm``, etc.)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:481
msgid "Why is the File System API is not available when I build with closure?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:483
msgid ""
"The :term:`Closure Compiler` will minify the File Server API code. Code that "
"uses the file system must be optimized **with** the File System API, using "
"emcc's ``--pre-js`` :ref:`option <emcc-pre-js>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:489
msgid ""
"Why does my code break and gives odd errors when using ``-O2 --closure 1``?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:491
msgid ""
"The :term:`Closure Compiler` minifies variable names, which results in very "
"short variable names like ``i``, ``j``, ``xa``, etc. If other code declares "
"variables with the same names in global scope, this can cause serious "
"problems."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:495
msgid ""
"This is likely to be the cause if you can successfully run code compiled "
"with ``-O2`` set and ``--closure`` unset."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:498
msgid ""
"One solution is to stop using small variable names in the global scope "
"(often this is a mistake — forgetting to use ``var`` when assigning to a "
"variable)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:501
msgid ""
"Another alternative is to wrap the generated code (or your other code) in a "
"closure, as shown:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:515
msgid "Why do I get ``TypeError: Module.someThing is not a function``?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:517
msgid ""
"The ``Module`` object will contain exported methods. For something to appear "
"there, you should add it to ``EXPORTED_FUNCTIONS`` for compiled code, or "
"``EXPORTED_RUNTIME_METHODS`` for a runtime method (like ``getValue``). For "
"example,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:526
msgid ""
"would export a C method ``my_func`` (in addition to ``main``, in this "
"example). And"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:532
msgid ""
"will export ``ccall``. In both cases you can then access the exported "
"function on the ``Module`` object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:534
msgid ""
"You can use runtime methods directly, without exporting them, if the "
"compiler can see them used. For example, you can use ``getValue`` in "
"``EM_ASM`` code, or a ``--pre-js``, by calling it directly. The optimizer "
"will not remove that JS runtime method because it sees it is used. You only "
"need to use ``Module.getValue`` if you want to call that method from outside "
"the JS code the compiler can see, and then you need to export it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:541
msgid ""
"Emscripten used to export many runtime methods by default. This increased "
"code size, and for that reason we've changed that default. If you depend on "
"something that used to be exported, you should see a warning pointing you to "
"the solution, in an unoptimized build, or a build with ``ASSERTIONS`` "
"enabled, which we hope will minimize any annoyance. See ``ChangeLog.md`` for "
"details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:552
msgid ""
"Why does ``Runtime`` no longer exist? Why do I get an error trying to access "
"``Runtime.someThing``?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:554
msgid ""
"1.37.27 includes a refactoring to remove the ``Runtime`` object. This makes "
"the generated code more efficient and compact, but requires minor changes if "
"you used ``Runtime.*`` APIs. You just need to remove the ``Runtime.`` "
"prefix, as those functions are now simple functions in the top scope (an "
"error message in ``-O0`` or builds with assertions enabled with suggest "
"this). In other words, replace"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:565
msgid "with"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:571
msgid ""
"The above will work for code in a ``--pre-js`` or JS library, that is, code "
"that is compiled together with the emscripten output. If you try to access "
"``Runtime.*`` methods from outside the compiled code, then you must export "
"that function (using ``EXPORTED_RUNTIME_METHODS``), and use it on the Module "
"object, see :ref:`that FAQ entry<faq-export-stuff>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:579
msgid ""
"Why do I get a ``NameError`` or ``a problem occurred in evaluating content "
"after a \"-s\"`` when I use a ``-s`` option?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:581
msgid ""
"This can occur if you have non-trivial strings in ``-s`` argument and are "
"having trouble getting the shell quoting / escaping correct."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:584
msgid ""
"Using the simpler list form (without quotes, spaces or square brackets) can "
"sometimes help:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:591
msgid "It is also possible to use a **response file**, that is,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:597
msgid ""
"with ``extra.txt`` being a plain text file that contains ``foo`` and ``bar`` "
"on separate lines."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:601
msgid "How do I specify ``-s`` options in a CMake project?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:603
msgid "Simple things like this should just work in a ``CMakeLists.txt`` file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:609
msgid ""
"However, some ``-s`` options may require quoting, or the space between ``-"
"s`` and the next argument may confuse CMake, when using things like "
"``target_link_options``. To avoid those problems, you can use ``-sX=Y`` "
"notation, that is, without spaces and without square brackets or quotes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:621
msgid ""
"Note also that ``_main`` does not need to be quoted, even though it's a "
"string name (``emcc`` knows that the argument to ``EXPORTED_FUNCTIONS`` is a "
"list of strings, so it accepts ``a`` or ``a,b`` etc.)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:627
msgid ""
"Why do I get a Python ``SyntaxError: invalid syntax`` on ``file=..`` or on a "
"string starting with ``f'..'``?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:629
msgid ""
"Emscripten requires a recent-enough version of Python. An older Python "
"version, like ``2.*``, will not support the print statement by default, so "
"it will error on syntax like ``print('..', file=..)``. And an older ``3.*`` "
"Python may not support f-strings, which look like ``f'..'``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:634
msgid ""
"Make sure that you have a new enough version of Python installed, as "
"specified in the :ref:`SDK <sdk-download-and-install>` instructions, and "
"that it is used by emcc (for example by running ``emcc.py`` using that "
"Python)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:638
msgid ""
"In a CI environment you may need to specify the Python version to use, if "
"the default is not new enough. For example, `on Netlify <https://github.com/"
"emscripten-core/emscripten/issues/12896>`_ you can use ``PYTHON_VERSION``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:645
msgid ""
"Why do I get a stack size error when optimizing: ``RangeError: Maximum call "
"stack size exceeded`` or similar?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:647
msgid "You may need to increase the stack size for :term:`node.js`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:649
msgid ""
"On Linux and Mac macOS, you can just do ``NODE_JS = ['/path/to/node', '--"
"stack_size=8192']`` in the :ref:`compiler-configuration-file`. On Windows "
"(for node versions older than v19), you will also need ``--max-stack-"
"size=8192``, and also run ``editbin /stack:33554432 node.exe``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:656
msgid "How do I pass int64_t and uint64_t values from js into Wasm functions?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:658
msgid ""
"If you build using the `-sWASM_BIGINT` flag, then `int64_t` and `uint64_t` "
"will be represented as `bigint` values in JS. Without the `-sWASM_BIGINT` "
"flag, the values will be represented as `number` in JS which can't represent "
"int64s, so what happens is that in exported functions (that you can call "
"from JS) we \"legalize\" the types, by turning an i64 argument into two i32s "
"(low and high bits), and an i64 return value becomes an i32, and you can "
"access the high bits by calling a helper function called getTempRet0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:668
msgid "Can I use multiple Emscripten-compiled programs on one Web page?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:670
msgid ""
"Emscripten output by default is just some code. When put in a script tag, "
"that means the code is in the global scope. So multiple such modules on the "
"same page can't work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:674
msgid ""
"But by putting each module in a function scope, that problem is avoided. "
"Emscripten even has a compile flag for this, ``MODULARIZE``, useful in "
"conjunction with ``EXPORT_NAME`` (details in settings.js)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:678
msgid ""
"However, there are still some issues if the same Module object (that defines "
"the canvas, text output area, etc.) is used among separate modules. By "
"default Emscripten output even looks for Module in the global scope, but "
"when using ``MODULARIZE``, you get a function you must call with the Module "
"as a param, so that problem is avoided. But note that each module will "
"probably want its own canvas, text output area, etc.; just passing in the "
"same Module object (e.g. from the default HTML shell) may not work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:686
msgid ""
"So by using ``MODULARIZE`` and creating a proper Module object for each "
"module, and passing those in, multiple modules can work fine."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:689
msgid ""
"Another option is to use an iframe, in which case the default HTML shell "
"will just work, as each will have its own canvas, etc. But this is overkill "
"for small programs, which can run modularly as described above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:695
msgid "Can I build JavaScript that only runs on the Web?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:697
msgid ""
"Yes, you can use the `ENVIRONMENT` option in ``settings.js``. For example, "
"building with ``emcc -sENVIRONMENT=web`` will emit code that only runs on "
"the Web, and does not include support code for Node.js and other "
"environments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/FAQ.rst:701
msgid ""
"This can be useful to reduce code size, and also works around issues like "
"the Node.js support code using ``require()``, which Webpack will process and "
"include unnecessary code for."
msgstr ""

